# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: beurla-reagaird
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:beurla-reagaird/ancient-belgian-language] The borders of the Belgian Sprachraum are made up by the Canche and the Authie in the south-west, the Weser and the Aller in the east, and the Ardennes and the German Mittelgebirge in the south-east.
[src:beurla-reagaird/ancient-belgian-language] Some scholars associate it with the Nordwestblock, more specifically with the Hilversum culture.
[src:beurla-reagaird/ancient-belgian-language] The use of the name *Belgian* for the language is to some extent supported by Julius Caesar's *De Bello Gallico*.
[src:beurla-reagaird/ancient-belgian-language] Caesar mentions that the Belgae and the Galli spoke different languages, which is partially supported by toponyms in present-day Belgium, which, according to Kuhn, point at the existence of an Indo-European language, distinct from Celtic and Germanic languages.
[src:beurla-reagaird/ancient-belgian-language] Hans Kuhn also noted certain connections (suffixes, ethnonyms, toponyms, anthroponyms) between this language and the Indo-European languages of southern Europe, in particular with the Italic languages.
[src:beurla-reagaird/ancient-belgian-language] Before their migration to the south, the Italics might have resided in central Europe, in the vicinity of the Germans, Celts and the Slavs, as shown by the amount of vocabulary common to these groups.
[src:beurla-reagaird/ancient-belgian-language] Some of them may have migrated to the northwest, while the others headed for the Italian peninsula.
[src:beurla-reagaird/ancient-belgian-language] Proponents of the Belgian language hypothesis also suggest that it was influenced by Germanic languages during a first, early Germanicisation in the 3rd century BC, distinct from the Frankish colonization in the 5th to the 8th centuries AD.
[src:beurla-reagaird/ancient-belgian-language] For example, the Germanic sound shifts (p → f, t → th, k → h, ŏ → ă) have affected toponyms that supposedly have a Belgian-language origin.
[src:beurla-reagaird/ancient-belgian-language] Characteristics of Belgian are said to include the retention of *p* after the sound shifts, a trait that it shared with the Lusitanian language.
[src:beurla-reagaird/ancient-belgian-language] Names of bodies of water ending in -*ara*, as in the name for the Dender; -*ănā* or -*ŏnā*, as in *Matrŏnā* (Marne River and also the current Mater) and settlement names ending in -*iŏm* are supposedly typically Belgian as well.
[src:beurla-reagaird/ancient-belgian-language] According to Gysseling, traces of Belgian are still visible.
[src:beurla-reagaird/ancient-belgian-language] The diminutive suffix -*ika*, the feminizing suffixes -*agjōn* and -*astrjō* and the collective suffix -*itja* have been incorporated in Dutch, sometimes very productively.
[src:beurla-reagaird/ancient-belgian-language] In toponymy, *apa*, *poel*, *broek*, *gaver*, *drecht*, *laar* and *ham* are retained as Belgian loanwords.
[src:beurla-reagaird/ancient-belgian-language] The language is mostly seen as Celtic, due to Celtic tribe names of later Belgae or Para-Celtic features similar to Lusitanian, and sometimes as Germanic.
[src:beurla-reagaird/ancient-belgian-language] Linguists proposed that *Belgian* was distinct from the Celtic and Germanic languages; some see it as a non-Indo-European language related to Tyrsenian, while others suggest a distinct Indo-European branch, similar to the case with Lusitanian.
[src:beurla-reagaird/ancient-belgian-language] Similarly, an alternative view suggests that *Belgian* was the result of an interaction between different substrates and time periods, that started resembling a distinct language, despite not being one.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Breton is an Insular Celtic language that was brought from Great Britain to Brittany by migrating Britons during the Early Middle Ages, which makes Breton most closely related to Cornish, another Southwestern Brittonic language.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Welsh and the extinct Cumbric, both Western Brittonic languages, are more distantly related, and the Goidelic languages (Irish, Manx, and Scottish Gaelic) have a slight connection due to their origins being from Insular Celtic.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Having declined from more than one million speakers around 1950 to 107,000 in 2024, Breton is classified as "severely endangered" by the UNESCO *Atlas of the World's Languages in Danger*.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] The number of children attending bilingual classes rose 33% between 2006 and 2012 to 14,709.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Breton is spoken in Lower Brittany (Breton: *Breizh-Izel*), roughly to the west of a line linking Plouha (west of Saint-Brieuc) and La Roche-Bernard (east of Vannes).
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] It comes from a Brittonic language community that once extended from Great Britain to Armorica (present-day Brittany) and had even established a toehold in Galicia (in present-day Spain).
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Old Breton is attested from the 9th century.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] It was the language of the upper classes until the 12th century after which it became the language of commoners in Lower Brittany.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] The nobility, followed by the bourgeoisie, adopted French.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] The written language of the Duchy of Brittany was Latin until it switched to French in the 15th century.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] There is a limited tradition of Breton literature.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Some philosophical and scientific terms in Modern Breton come from Old Breton.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] The recognized stages of the Breton language are **Old Breton** – c.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] The French monarchy was not concerned with the minority languages of France, which were spoken by the lower classes, and required the use of French for government business as part of its policy of national unity.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] During the French Revolution, the government introduced policies favouring French over the regional languages, which it pejoratively referred to as *patois*.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] The revolutionaries assumed that reactionary and monarchist forces preferred regional languages to keep the peasant masses underinformed.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] In 1794, Bertrand Barère submitted his "report on the *patois*" to the Committee of Public Safety in which he said that "federalism and superstition speak Breton".
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Under the Third, Fourth and early Fifth Republics, the French government attempted to stamp out regional languages - including Breton — in state schools, in an effort to build a unified national culture.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Teachers humiliated students for using their regional languages, and such practices prevailed until the late 1960s.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] In the early 21st century, the political centralization of France, the influence of the media and the increasing mobility of people have caused only about 200,000 people to be active speakers of Breton, a dramatic decline from more than 1 million in 1950.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Most of today's speakers are more than 60 years old, and Breton is now classified as an endangered language.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] In the early 20th century, half of the population of Lower Brittany knew only Breton; the other half were bilingual.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] By 1950, there were only 100,000 monolingual Bretons, and the rapid decline has continued, with likely no monolingual speakers left today.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] A statistical survey in 1997 found around 300,000 speakers in Lower Brittany of whom about 190,000 were aged 60 or older.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] In 1993, parents were finally legally allowed to give their children Breton names.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] In 1925, Professor Roparz Hemon founded the Breton-language review *Gwalarn*.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] During its 19-year run, *Gwalarn* tried to raise the language to the level of a great international language.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Its publication encouraged the creation of original literature in all genres, and proposed Breton translations of internationally recognized foreign works.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Other Breton-language periodicals have been published, which established a fairly large body of literature for a minority language.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] In 1977, Diwan schools were founded to teach Breton by immersion.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Since their establishment, Diwan schools have provided fully-immersive primary school and partially-immersive secondary school instruction in Breton for thousands of students across Brittany.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] This has directly contributed to the growing numbers of school-age speakers of Breton.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] The *Asterix* comic series has been translated into Breton.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] According to the comic, the Gaulish village where Asterix lives is in the Armorica peninsula, which is now Brittany.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Some other popular comics have also been translated into Breton, including *The Adventures of Tintin*, *Spirou*, *Titeuf*, *Hägar the Horrible*, *Peanuts* and *Yakari*.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Some original media are created in Breton.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Radio Kerne, broadcasting from Finistère, has exclusively Breton programming.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Some movies (*Lancelot du Lac*, *Shakespeare in Love*, *Marion du Faouet*, *Sezneg*) and TV series (*Columbo*, *Perry Mason*) have also been translated and broadcast in Breton.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Poets, singers, linguists, and writers who have written in Breton, including Yann-Ber Kallocʼh, Roparz Hemon, Añjela Duval, Xavier de Langlais, Pêr-Jakez Helias, Youenn Gwernig, Glenmor, Vefa de Saint-Pierre and Alan Stivell are now known internationally.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Today, Breton is the only living Celtic language that is not recognized by a national government as an official or regional language.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] The first Breton dictionary, the *Catholicon*, was also the first French dictionary.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Edited by Jehan Lagadec in 1464, it was a trilingual work containing Breton, French and Latin.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Today bilingual dictionaries have been published for Breton and languages including English, Dutch, German, Spanish and Welsh.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] A monolingual dictionary, *Geriadur Brezhoneg an Here* was published in 1995.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] The first edition contained about 10,000 words, and the second edition of 2001 contains 20,000 words.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] In the early 21st century, the *Ofis Publik ar Brezhoneg* ("Public Office for the Breton language") began a campaign to encourage daily use of Breton in the region by both businesses and local communes.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Efforts include installing bilingual signs and posters for regional events, as well as encouraging the use of the Spilhennig to let speakers identify each other.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] The office also started an Internationalization and localization policy asking Google, Firefox and SPIP to develop their interfaces in Breton.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] In 2004, the Breton Wikipedia started, which counts just over 90,000 articles as of December 2025.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] In March 2007, the *Ofis ar Brezhoneg* signed a tripartite agreement with Regional Council of Brittany and Microsoft for the consideration of the Breton language in Microsoft products.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] In October 2014, Facebook added Breton as one of its 121 languages after three years of talks between the *Ofis* and Facebook.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] France has twice chosen to enter the Eurovision Song Contest with songs in Breton; once in 1996 in Oslo with "*Diwanit bugale*" by Dan Ar Braz and the fifty piece band Héritage des Celtes, and most recently in 2022 in Turin with "*Fulenn*" by Alvan Morvan Rosius and vocal trio Ahez.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] These are two of five times France has chosen songs in one of its minority languages for the contest, the others being in 1992 (bilingual French and Antillean Creole), 1993 (bilingual French and Corsican), and 2011 (Corsican).
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Breton is spoken mainly in Lower Brittany but also in a more dispersed way in Upper Brittany (where it is spoken alongside Gallo and French), and in areas around the world that have Breton emigrants.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] The four traditional dialects of Breton correspond to medieval bishoprics, rather than to linguistic divisions.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] They are *leoneg* (*léonard*, of the county of Léon), *tregerieg* (*trégorrois*, of Trégor), *kerneveg* (*cornouaillais*, of *Cornouaille*), and *gwenedeg* (*vannetais*, of Vannes).
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] *Gwerranneg* (*guérandais*, of Guérande) was spoken up to the beginning of the 20th century in the region of Guérande and Batz-sur-Mer.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] There are no clear boundaries between the dialects because they form a dialect continuum and vary only slightly from one village to the next.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] *Gwenedeg*, however, requires a little study to be intelligible with most of the other dialects.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Due to this difficulty in intelligibility, the Glottolog project split the Gwenedeg dialects into a separate language entry from the KLT Breton dialects in v5.2 under the name Vannetais.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] French is the sole official language of France.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Supporters of Breton and other minority languages continue to argue for their recognition and for their place in education, public schools, and public life.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] In July 2008, the legislature amended the French Constitution, adding article 75-1: *les langues régionales appartiennent au patrimoine de la France* (the regional languages belong to the heritage of France).
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] The European Charter for Regional or Minority Languages, which obliges signatory states to recognize minority and regional languages, was signed by France in 1999 but has not been ratified.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] On 27 October 2015, the Senate rejected a draft constitutional law ratifying the charter.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Regional and departmental authorities use Breton to a very limited extent.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Some bilingual signage has also been installed such as street name signs in Breton towns.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Under the Toubon Law, it is illegal for commercial signage to be in Breton alone.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Signs must be bilingual or only in French.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Since commercial signage usually has limited physical space, most businesses have signs only in French.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] In the late 20th century, the French government considered incorporating the independent Breton-language immersion schools (called *Diwan*) into the state education system.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] This action was blocked by the French Constitutional Council based on the 1994 amendment to the Constitution that establishes French as the language of the republic.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Therefore, no other language may be used as a language of instruction in state schools.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] The Toubon Law implemented the amendment, asserting that French is the language of public education.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] The Diwan schools were founded in Brittany in 1977 to teach Breton by immersion.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Since their establishment, Diwan schools have provided fully immersive primary school and partially immersive secondary school instruction in Breton for thousands of students across Brittany.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] The schools have also gained fame from their high level of results in school exams, including those on French language and literature.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Breton-language schools do not receive funding from the national government, though the Brittany Region may fund them.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Another teaching method is a bilingual approach by *Div Yezh* ("Two Languages") in the State schools, created in 1979.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] *Dihun* ("Awakening") was created in 1990 for bilingual education in the Catholic schools.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] In 2018, 18,337 pupils (about 2% of all students in Brittany) attended *Diwan*, *Div Yezh* and *Dihun* schools, and their number has increased yearly.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] In 2007, some 4,500 to 5,000 adults followed an evening or correspondence one Breton-language course.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] The transmission of Breton in 1999 was estimated to be 3 percent.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] In addition to bilingual education (including Breton-medium education), the region has introduced the Breton language in primary education, mainly in the department of Finistère.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] The "initiation" sessions are generally one to three hours per week and consist of songs and games.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Schools in secondary education (*collèges* and *lycées*) offer some courses in Breton.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] In 2010, nearly 5,000 students in Brittany were reported to be taking this option.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Additionally, the University of Rennes 2 has a Breton-language department, which offers courses in the language, along with a master's degree in Breton and Celtic Studies.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] All unstressed vowels are short; stressed vowels can be short or long.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] (Vowel length is not noted in usual orthographies, as it is implicit in the phonology of particular dialects, and not all dialects pronounce stressed vowels as long.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] An emergence of a schwa sound occurs as a result of vowel neutralization in post-tonic position in different dialects.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] The first extant Breton texts, contained in the Leyden manuscript, were written at the end of the 8th century, 50 years prior to the Strasbourg Oaths, which are considered to be the earliest example of French.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Like many medieval orthographies, Old and Middle Breton had an orthography that was at first not standardised, and the spelling of a particular word varied at the author's discretion.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] In 1499, however, the *Catholicon*, was published; as the first dictionary written for both French and Breton, it became a point of reference on how to transcribe the language.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] As phonetic and phonological differences between the dialects began to magnify, many regions, particularly the Vannes country, began to devise their own orthographies.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Many of those orthographies were more closely related to the French model albeit with some modifications.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Examples of modifications include the replacement of Old Breton -⟨z⟩ with -⟨h⟩ to denote word-final /x~h/ (an evolution of Old Breton /θ/ in the Vannes dialect) and the use of -⟨h⟩ to denote the initial mutation of /k/ (today, this mutation is written ⟨cʼh⟩).
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] In the 1830s, Jean-François Le Gonidec created a modern phonetic system for the language.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] During the early 20th century, a group of writers known as *Emglev ar Skrivanerien* elaborated and reformed Le Gonidec's system.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] They made it more suitable as a super-dialectal representation of the dialects of Cornouaille, Leon and Trégor (known as from *Kernev*, *Leon* and *Treger* in Breton).
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] This **KLT** orthography was established in 1911.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] At the same time, writers of the more divergent Vannetais dialect developed a phonetic system, which was also based on that of Le Gonidec.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Following proposals that had been made during the 1920s, the KLT and Vannetais orthographies were merged in 1941 to create an orthographic system to represent all four dialects.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] This *Peurunvan* ("wholly unified") orthography was significant for the inclusion of the digraph ⟨zh⟩, which represents a /h/ in Vannetais and corresponds to a /z/ in the KLT dialects.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] In 1955, François Falcʼhun and the group Emgleo Breiz proposed a new orthography, which was designed to use a set of graphemes closer to the conventions of French.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] This *Orthographe universitaire* ("University Orthography", known in Breton as *Skolveurieg*) was given official recognition by the French authorities as the "official orthography of Breton in French education".
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] It was opposed in the region and was only by the magazine *Brud Nevez* and the publishing house Emgleo Breiz, which disappeared in 2015.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] In the 1970s, a new standard orthography was devised: the *etrerannyezhel* or *interdialectale*.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] This system is based on the derivation of the words.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Today, most writers continue to use the *Peurunvan orthography*, and it is the version taught in most Breton-language schools.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] The circumflex, grave accent, trema and tilde appear on some letters.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Both orthographies use the above alphabet although ⟨é⟩ is used only in *Skolveurieg*.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Differences between the two systems are particularly noticeable in word endings.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] In Peurunvan, final obstruents, which are devoiced in absolute final position and voiced in sandhi before voiced sounds, are represented by a grapheme that indicates a voiceless sound.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] In OU they are written as voiced but represented as voiceless before suffixes: *braz* "big", *brasocʼh* "bigger".
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] In addition, Peurunvan maintains the KLT convention, which distinguishes noun/adjective pairs by nouns written with a final voiced consonant and adjectives with a voiceless one.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] No distinction is made in pronunciation. e.g., *brezhoneg* 'Breton language' vs.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] **^** Unwritten lenition of ⟨ch, cʼh, f, s⟩ and spirantization of ⟨p⟩ > ⟨f⟩ [v].
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] **^** Unstressed ⟨e, eu, o⟩ represent [ɛ, œ, ɔ] in Leoneg but [e, ø, o] in the other dialects.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] The realisations [ɛ̞, œ̞, ɔ̞] appear mainly before ⟨rr⟩ (also less often before ⟨cʼh⟩), semivowels [j, w], consonant clusters beginning with ⟨r⟩ or ⟨l⟩.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Stressed long ⟨e, eu, o⟩ represent [eː, øː, oː].
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] In the case of word-final ⟨g⟩ and ⟨k⟩ palatalization to [c] also occurs after ⟨i⟩.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] **^** Before a vowel other than ⟨i⟩ the digraph ⟨ni⟩ is written instead of ⟨gn⟩, e.g.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] *bleniañ* "to drive", radical *blegn*, 1PS preterite *blegnis*, 3PS preterite *blenias*.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] **^** ⟨i⟩ is realized as [j] when it precedes or follows a vowel (or when between vowels), but in words such as *l**i**en*, *l**i**orzh*, *rakd**i**azezañ* it represents [iː] (in orthography ⟨ï⟩ may be used: *lïen*, *lïorzh*, *rakdïazezañ*).
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] **^** ⟨ilh⟩ represents [ʎ] when it follows a vowel, after a consonant it represents [iʎ].
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] But before a vowel other than ⟨i⟩, ⟨li⟩ is written instead of ⟨ilh⟩, e.g.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] *heuliañ* "to follow", radical *heuilh*, 1PS preterite *heuilhis*, 3PS preterite *heulias*.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] In some regions [j] may be heard instead of [ʎ].
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] **^** Word-finally after a cluster of unvoiced consonants.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] **^** The digraph ⟨ou⟩ is realized like ⟨w⟩ when preceded or followed by a vowel (or when between vowels), but in words such as *Doue*, *douar*, *gouarn* it represents [uː].
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] **^** The digraph ⟨où⟩ represents plural endings.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Its pronunciation varies by dialect: [u, o, ø, ow, aw, aɥ, ɔɥ] rating geographically from Northwest Leon to Southeast Gwened.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] **^** ⟨v⟩ usually represents [v], but word-finally (except in word-final ⟨ñv⟩) it represents [w] in KLT, [ɥ] in Gwenedeg and [f] in Goëlo.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] The pronunciation [v] is retained word-finally in verbs.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Word-finally following ⟨r, l, n, z⟩ it represents [o].
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] **^** Used to distinguish words such as *stêr* "river", *hêr* "heir", *kêr* "town" (also written *kaer*) from *ster* "sense", *her* "bold", *ker* "dear".
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] **^** Used to distinguish *trôad* "circuit/tour" from *troad* "foot".
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] **^** In northern dialects (mainly in Leoneg), there is a tendency to voice ⟨cʼh⟩ between vowels. [ɣ] also appears as the lenition of ⟨g, cʼh⟩ and mixed mutation of ⟨g⟩.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] **^** The lenition of ⟨d⟩ and the spirantization of ⟨t⟩ are both represented by ⟨z⟩ is mainly pronounced [z] although in certain regions [s] (especially for the spirantization of ⟨t⟩ in Cornouaille) and [ð] (in some Haut-Vannetais varieties)31 also occur.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] **^** The pronunciation of ⟨r⟩ varies by dialect, nowadays uvular [ʀ] (or [ʁ]) is standard; [r] occurs in Leoneg, [ɾ] or [ɹ] in Tregerieg, and [ʀ], [ʁ], [r], and [ɾ] in Gwenedeg.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] **^** In Gwenedeg an unstressed ⟨e⟩ often represents [ə].
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] **^** Lenited varieties of ⟨r, l, n⟩ may appear word-initially in case of soft mutation.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] **^** In Leoneg [u(ː)] in front of a nasal.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] **^** In Leoneg ⟨w⟩ represents [v] before ⟨e, i⟩.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] **^** A conservative realisation of the initial mutation of ⟨d⟩ and ⟨t⟩, used in certain parts of the Vannes country.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Breton nouns are marked for gender and number.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] While Breton has a fairly typical gender system for Western Europe, Breton has number markers that demonstrate rarer behaviors.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Breton has two genders: masculine (*gourel*) and feminine (*gwregel*).
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] It has largely lost its historic neuter (*nepreizh*), as has also occurred in the other Celtic languages and in the Romance languages.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Certain suffixes (*-ach/-aj, -(a)dur, -er, -lecʼh, -our, -ti, -va*) are masculine, while others (*-enti, -er, -ez, -ezh, -ezon, -i*, *-eg*, *-ell*, and the singulative *-enn*) are feminine.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] The suffix *-eg* can be masculine or feminine.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] There are certain non-determinant factors that influence gender assignment.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Biological sex is applied for animate referents.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Metals, time divisions (except for *eur* "hour", *noz* "night" and *sizhun* "week") and mountains tend to be masculine, while rivers, cities and countries tend to be feminine.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] However, gender assignment to certain words often varies between dialects.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Number in Breton is primarily based on an opposition between singular and plural.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] However, the system is full of complexities in how the distinction is realized.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Although modern Breton has lost the dual number as a productive grammatical category, remnants of its use are preserved in certain nouns referring to paired body parts such as for eyes, ears, cheeks, legs, armpits, arms, hands, knees, thighs and wings.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Those forms typically feature a prefix (*daou-*, *di-* or *div-*), which is etymologically derived from the numeral two.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] The dual number is no longer a productive feature of Breton grammar and survives only in a lexicalized form.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Certain words such as *daoulagad* ('eyes') and *divskouarn* ('ears') are historically dual in origin.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] These forms can nevertheless undergo pluralization once more to yield *daoulagadoù* ('pairs of eyes') and *diskouarnoù* ('pairs of ears').
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Like other Brythonic languages, Breton has a singulative suffix, which forms singulars out of collective nouns for which the morphologically less complex form is the plural.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Thus, the singulative of the collective *logod* "mice" is *logod**enn*** "mouse".
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] "Breton exhibits a more complex system than Welsh in this respect.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Collective nouns can undergo pluralization, yielding forms with meanings distinct from the base collective.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] For example, *pesk* ('fish', singular) forms the collective plural *pesked* ('fish'), which may then be singulativized as *peskedenn* to denote an individual fish from a group.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] "In addition, the Breton plural system is complicated by the existence of two distinct pluralizing functions.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Alongside the 'default' plural, there is a second formation used to convey a sense of variety or diversity.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] As a result, a single noun may yield two semantically different plurals; for example, *park* ('park') forms *parkoù* ('parks') and *parkeier* ('various different parks')." Ball reports that the latter pluralizer is used only for inanimate nouns.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Certain formations have been lexicalized to have meanings other than that which might be predicted solely from the morphology: *dour* "water" pluralized forms *dourioù* which means not "waters" but instead "rivers", while *doureier* now has come to mean "running waters after a storm".
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Certain forms have lost the singular from their paradigm: *keloù* means "news" and **kel* is not used, while *keleier* has become the regular plural, 'different news items'.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Meanwhile, certain nouns can form doubly marked plurals with lexicalized meanings – *bugel* "child" is pluralized once into *bugale* "children" and then pluralized a second time to make *bugaleoù* "groups of children".
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] As seen elsewhere in many Celtic languages, the formation of the plural can be difficult to predict, being determined by a mix of semantic, morphological and lexical factors.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] The most common plural marker is *-où*, with its variant *-ioù*; most nouns that use that marker are inanimates, but collectives of both inanimate and animate nouns always use it as well.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Most animate nouns, including trees, have a plural in *-ed*.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] However, in some dialects the use of this affix has become rare.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Various masculine nouns including occupations, as well as the word *Saoz* ("Englishman", plural *Saozon*), take the suffix *-ien*, with a range of variants including *-on*, *-ion*, *-an* and *-ian*.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] The rare pluralizing suffixes *-er*/*-ier* and *-i* are used for a few nouns.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Various nouns instead form their plural merely with ablaut: *a* or *o* in the stem is changed to *e*: *askell* "wing" → *eskell* "wings"; *dant* "tooth" → *dent* "teeth"; *kordenn* "rope" → *kerdenn* "ropes".
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Another set of nouns have lexicalized plurals that bear little if any resemblance to their singulars.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] These include *placʼh* "girl" → *mercʼhed*, *porcʼhell* "pig" → *mocʼh*, *buocʼh* "cow" → *saout*, and *ki* "dog" → *chas*.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] In compound nouns, the head noun, which usually comes first, is pluralized.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Like in other modern Celtic languages, Breton pronouns are fused into preceding prepositions to produce a sort of inflected preposition.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] In the examples above, the Goidelic languages (Irish, Scottish Gaelic, and Manx) use the preposition meaning *at* to show possession, and the Brittonic languages use the one meaning *with*.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] The Goidelic languages, however, use the preposition *with* to express "belong to" (Irish *is liom an leabhar*, Scottish *is leam an leabhar*, Manx *s'lhiams yn lioar*, The book belongs to me).
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] The Welsh examples are in literary Welsh.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] The order and the preposition may differ slightly in Colloquial Welsh (Formal *mae car gennym*, North Wales *mae gynnon ni gar*, South Wales *mae car gyda ni*).
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Breton has four initial consonant mutations.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Though modern Breton lost the nasal mutation of Welsh (but for rare words such the word "door": "dor" "an nor"), it also has a "hard" mutation, which has voiced stops become voiceless, and a "mixed" mutation, which is a mixture of hard and soft mutations.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Normal word order, like the other Insular Celtic languages, is at its core VSO (verb-subject-object), which is most apparent in embedded clauses.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] However, Breton finite verbs in main clauses are additionally subject to V2 word order in which the finite main clause verb is typically the second element in the sentence.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] In fact, starting a sentence with a finite verb is generally ungrammatical in Breton.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Noun phrases, adverbial phrases, verbal nouns and the negative particle *ne* may stand in sentence-initial position to satisfy the V2 requirement.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] That makes it perfectly possible to put the subject or the object at the beginning of the sentence, largely depending on the focus of the speaker.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Breton uses much more borrowed vocabulary than its relatives further north; by some estimates a full 40% of its core vocabulary consists of loanwords from French.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] The English words dolmen and menhir have been borrowed from French, which took them from Breton.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] However, this is uncertain: for instance, menhir is *peulvan* or *maen hir* ("long stone"), *maen sav* ("straight stone") (two words: noun + adjective) in Breton.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] *Dolmen* is a misconstructed word (it should be *taol-**v**aen*).
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Some studies state that these words were borrowed from Cornish.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] *Maen hir* can be directly translated from Welsh as "long stone" (which is exactly what a menhir or *maen hir* is).
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] The Cornish surnames Mennear, Minear and Manhire all derive from the Cornish *men* *hyr* ("long stone"), as does *Tremenheere* "settlement by the long stone".
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] The French word *baragouiner* ("to jabber in a foreign language or an unintelligible manner") is derived from Breton *bara* ("bread") and *gwin* ("wine").
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] The French word *goéland* ("large seagull") is derived from Breton *gwelan*, which shares the same root as English "gull" (Welsh *gwylan*, Cornish *goelann*).
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Hon Tad, cʼhwi hag a zo en Neñv, ra vo santelaet hocʼh anv.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Ra vo graet ho youl war an douar evel en neñv.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Distaolit dimp hon dleoù evel m'hor bo ivez distaolet d'hon dleourion.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p01] Ha n'hon lezit ket da vont gant an temptadur, met hon dieubit eus an Droug.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p02] .bzh is an approved Internet generic top-level domains intended for Brittany and the Breton culture and languages.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p02] In 2023, the Breton internet extension .bzh had more than 12,000 registrations.
[src:beurla-reagaird/breton-language-p02] Alongside the promotion of the .bzh internet extension, the www.bzh association promotes other services to develop Brittany's image on the web: campaign for a Breton flag emoji (), and email service.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] The **Brittonic languages** (also **Brythonic** or **British Celtic**) form one of the two branches of the Insular Celtic languages; the other is Goidelic.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] It comprises the extant languages Breton, Cornish, and Welsh.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] The name *Brythonic* was derived by Welsh Celticist John Rhys from the Welsh word *Brython*, denoting a Celtic Briton as distinguished from Anglo-Saxons or Gaels.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] The Brittonic languages derive from the Common Brittonic language, spoken throughout Great Britain during the Iron Age and Roman period.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] In the 5th and 6th centuries emigrating Britons also took Brittonic speech to the continent, most significantly in Brittany and Britonia.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] Welsh and Breton continue to be spoken as native languages, while a revival in Cornish has led to an increase in speakers of that language.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] Cumbric and Pictish are extinct, having been replaced by Goidelic and Anglic speech.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] There is also a community of Brittonic language speakers in *Y Wladfa* (the Welsh settlement in Patagonia).
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] The names "Brittonic" and "Brythonic" are scholarly conventions referring to the Celtic languages of Britain and to the ancestral language they originated from, designated Common Brittonic, in contrast to the Goidelic languages originating in Ireland.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] Both were created in the 19th century to avoid the ambiguity of earlier terms such as "British" and "Cymric".
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] "Brythonic" was coined in 1879 by the Celticist John Rhys from the Welsh word *Brython*.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] "Brittonic", derived from "Briton" and also earlier spelled "Britonic" and "Britonnic", emerged later in the 19th century, though being attested in French (as "brittonique") as early as in 1834.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] "Brittonic" became more prominent through the 20th century, and was used in Kenneth H.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] Jackson's highly influential 1953 work on the topic, *Language and History in Early Britain*.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] Jackson noted by that time that "Brythonic" had become a dated term: "of late there has been an increasing tendency to use Brittonic instead." Today, "Brittonic" often replaces "Brythonic" in the literature.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] Rudolf Thurneysen used "Britannic" in his influential *A Grammar of Old Irish*, although this never became popular among subsequent scholars.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] Comparable historical terms include the Medieval Latin *lingua Britannica* and *sermo Britannicus* and the Welsh *Brythoneg*.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] Some writers use "British" for the language and its descendants, although, due to the risk of confusion, others avoid it or use it only in a restricted sense.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] Koch, use "British" only for the early phase of the Common Brittonic language.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] Before Jackson's work, "Brittonic" and "Brythonic" were often used for all the P-Celtic languages, including not just the varieties in Britain but those Continental Celtic languages that similarly experienced the evolution of the Proto-Celtic language element /kʷ/ to /p/.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] However, subsequent writers have tended to follow Jackson's scheme, rendering this use obsolete.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] The name "Britain" itself comes from Latin: *Britannia~Brittania*, via Old French *Bretaigne* and Middle English *Breteyne*, possibly influenced by Old English *Bryten[lond]*, probably also from Latin *Brittania*, ultimately an adaptation of the native word for the island, **Pritanī*.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] Knowledge of the Brittonic languages comes from a variety of sources.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] The early language's information is obtained from coins, inscriptions, and comments by classical writers as well as place names and personal names recorded by them.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] For later languages, there is information from medieval writers and modern native speakers, together with place names.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] The names recorded in the Roman period are given in Rivet and Smith.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] The Brittonic branch is also referred to as *P-Celtic* because linguistic reconstruction of the Brittonic reflex of the Proto-Indo-European phoneme **kʷ* is *p* as opposed to Goidelic *k*.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] Such nomenclature usually implies acceptance of the P-Celtic and Q-Celtic hypothesis rather than the Insular Celtic hypothesis because the term includes certain Continental Celtic languages as well.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] Brittonic languages in use today are Welsh, Cornish and Breton.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] Welsh and Breton have been spoken continuously since they formed.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] For all practical purposes Cornish died out during the 18th or 19th century, but a revival movement has more recently created small numbers of new speakers.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] Also notable are the extinct language Cumbric, and possibly the extinct Pritenic Pictish.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] One view, advanced in the 1950s and based on apparently unintelligible ogham inscriptions, was that the Picts may have also used a non-Indo-European language.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] This view, while attracting broad popular appeal, has virtually no following in contemporary linguistic scholarship.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] Pictish is more often considered to be a member of its own branch known as Pritenic, which is closer to Brythonic than to Goidelic, but distinct from both.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] The modern Brittonic languages are generally considered to all derive from a common ancestral language termed *Brittonic*, *British*, *Common Brittonic*, *Old Brittonic* or *Proto-Brittonic*, which is thought to have developed from Proto-Celtic or early Insular Celtic by the 6th century BC.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] A major archaeogenetics study uncovered a migration into southern Britain in the middle to late Bronze Age, during the 500-year period 1,300–800 BC.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] The newcomers were genetically most similar to ancient individuals from Gaul.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] During 1,000–875 BC, their genetic markers swiftly spread through southern Britain, but not northern Britain.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] The authors describe this as a "plausible vector for the spread of early Celtic languages into Britain".
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] There was much less inward migration during the Iron Age, so it is likely that Celtic reached Britain before then.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] Barry Cunliffe suggests that a Goidelic branch of Celtic may already have been spoken in Britain, but that this middle Bronze Age migration would have introduced the Brittonic branch.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] Brittonic languages were probably spoken before the Roman invasion throughout most of Great Britain.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] It might have been spoken on the Isle of Man, although by the early Middle Ages it had a Goidelic language, Manx.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] During the period of the Roman occupation of what is now England and Wales (AD 43 to c.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] Approximately 800 of these Latin loan-words have survived in the three modern Brittonic languages.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] Pictish might have resisted Latin influence to a greater extent than Brittonic languages, potentially splitting from Common Brythonic because of resistance, if wasn't separate from Brythonic before as Pritenic.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] It is probable that at the start of the Post-Roman period, Common Brittonic was differentiated into at least two major dialect groups – Southwestern and Western.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] Jackson showed that a few of the dialect distinctions between West and Southwest Brittonic go back a long way.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] New divergencies began around AD 500 but other changes that were shared occurred in the 6th century.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] Other common changes occurred in the 7th century onward and are possibly due to inherent tendencies.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] Thus the concept of a Common Brittonic language ends by AD 600.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] Substantial numbers of Britons certainly remained in the expanding area controlled by Anglo-Saxons, but over the fifth and sixth centuries they mostly adopted the Old English language and culture.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] Brittonic grammar had a case system similar to Irish and Scottish Gaelic and descending from Proto-Celtic, however this had vanished by the 6th century.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] The Brittonic languages spoken in what are now Scotland and England began to be displaced in the 5th century through the settlement of Irish-speaking Gaels and Germanic peoples.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] 1129 that Pictish was "no longer spoken", despite Pictish names appearing up to 14th century.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] The displacement of the languages of Brittonic descent was probably complete in all of Britain except Cornwall, Wales, and the English counties bordering these areas such as Devon, by the 11th century.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] Western Herefordshire continued to speak Welsh until the late nineteenth century, and isolated pockets of Shropshire speak Welsh today.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] The large array of Brittonic sound changes has been documented by Schrijver (1995), building upon Jackson (1953).
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] Brittonic has undergone an extensive remodeling of Proto-Celtic diphthongs and long vowels.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] All original Proto-Celtic diphthongs turned into monophthongs, albeit a number of these re-diphthongized at later stages.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] The distribution of Proto-Celtic short vowels were reshuffled by various processes in Brittonic, such as the two i-affections, a-affection, raisings, and contact with lenited consonants like **g* > /ɣ/ and **s* > **h*.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] Welsh exhibits raisings of **e* to **i* > **ɪ* > *ɨ* ⟨y⟩ and **o* > /u/ ⟨w⟩ before a nasal followed by a stop.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] It is difficult to determine whether the raising from **o* to **u* also affected Cornish and Breton, since both of those languages generally merge **o* with **u*.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] This raising preceded a-affection, since a-affection reverses this raising whenever it applied.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] All these raisings not only affected native vocabulary, but also affected Latin loanwords.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] Multiple special interactions of vowels occurred when followed by **g*.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] Closely paralleling the common Celtic change of **eRa* > **aRa* (Joseph's rule) is the change of **oRa* to **aRa* in Brittonic, with *R* standing for any lone sonorant.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] Unlike Joseph's rule, **oRa* to **aRa* did not occur in Goidelic.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] Assuming that Welsh *manach* (borrowed from Latin *monachus* "monk") also underwent this assimilation, Schrijver concludes that this change must predate the raising of vowels in **mVn-* sequences, which in turn predates a-affection (an early fifth-century process).
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] In Brittonic, Celtic **ye* generally became /ja/.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] The sequence **wo* was quite volatile in Brittonic.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] It originally manifested as **wo* in unlenited position and **wa* in lenited position.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] Word-initially, this allomorphy was gone in medieval times, leveled out in various ways.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] Whichever of **o* or **a* to be generalized in the reflexes of a word in a given Brittonic language is completely unpredictable, and occasionally both *o* and *a* reflexes have been attested within the same language.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] Southwest Brittonic languages like Breton and Cornish usually generalize the same variant of **wo* in a given word while Welsh tends to have its own distribution of variants.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] The distribution of **wo/wa* is also complicated by an Old Breton development where **wo* that had not turned to **gwa* would split into *go(u)-* (Old Breton *gu-*) in penultimate post-apocope syllables and *go-* in monosyllables.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] The sequence **ub* > **uβ* remained as such when followed by a consonant, for instance in Proto-Celtic **dubros* "water" > **duβr* > Welsh *dwfr*, *dŵr* and Breton *dour*.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] However, if no consonant exists after a **ub* sequence, the **u* merges with whatever Proto-Celtic **ou* and **oi* became, the result of which is written ⟨u⟩ in the Brittonic languages.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] The lenited **b* > **β* is lost word-finally after this happens.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] Schrijver dates this development between the 6th to 8th centuries, with subsequent loss of **β* datable to the 9th century.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] In Brittonic, final a-affection was triggered by final-syllable **ā* or **a*, which was later apocopated.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] This process lowered **i* and **u* in the preceding syllable to **e* and **o*, respectively.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] A-affection, by affecting feminine forms of adjectives and not their masculine counterparts, created root vowel alternations by gender such as **windos*, feminine **windā* > **gwɪnn*, feminine **gwenn* > Welsh *gwyn*, feminine *gwen*.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] There were two separate processes of i-affection in Brittonic, both causing fronting of vowels: **final i-affection** and **internal i-affection**.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] The regular consonantal sound changes from Proto-Celtic to Welsh, Cornish, and Breton are summarised in the following table.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] Where the graphemes have a different value from the corresponding IPA symbols, the IPA equivalent is indicated between slashes.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] V represents a vowel; C represents a consonant.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] The principal legacy left behind in those territories from which the Brittonic languages were displaced is that of toponyms (place names) and hydronyms (names of rivers and other bodies of water).
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] There are many Brittonic place names in lowland Scotland and in the parts of England where it is agreed that substantial Brittonic speakers remained (Brittonic names, apart from those of the former Romano-British towns, are scarce over most of England).
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] Names derived (sometimes indirectly) from Brittonic include London, Penicuik, Perth, Aberdeen, York, Dorchester, Dover, and Colchester.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] Brittonic elements found in England include *bre-* and *bal-* for 'hill', while some such as *co[o]mb[e]* (from *cwm*) for 'small deep valley' and *tor* for 'hill, rocky headland' are examples of Brittonic words that were borrowed into English.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] Others reflect the presence of Britons such as Dumbarton – from the Scottish Gaelic *Dùn Breatainn* meaning 'Fort of the Britons', and Walton meaning (in Anglo-Saxon) a *tun* 'settlement' where the *Wealh* 'Britons' still lived.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] The number of Celtic river names in England generally increases from east to west, a map showing these being given by Jackson.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] These include Avon, Chew, Frome, Axe, Brue and Exe, but also river names containing the elements *der-/dar-/dur-* and *-went* e.g.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] Derwent, Darwen, Deer, Adur, Dour, Darent, and Went.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] These names exhibit multiple different Celtic roots.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] One is **dubri-* 'water' (Breton *dour*, Cumbric *dowr*, Welsh *dŵr*), also found in the place-name Dover (attested in the Roman period as *Dubrīs*); this is the source of rivers named Dour.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] Another is deru̯o- 'oak' or 'true' (Bret.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] *derw*), coupled with two agent suffixes, *-ent* and *-iū*; this is the origin of Derwent, Darent, and Darwen (attested in the Roman period as Deru̯entiō).
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] The final root to be examined is *went/uent*.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] In Roman Britain, there were three tribal capitals named U̯entā (modern Winchester, Caerwent, and Caistor St Edmunds), whose meaning was 'place, town'.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] Tolkien, have argued that Celtic has acted as a substrate to English for both the lexicon and syntax.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] It is generally accepted that Brittonic effects on English are lexically few, aside from toponyms, consisting of a small number of domestic and geographical words, which "may" include *bin*, *brock*, *carr*, *comb*, *crag* and *tor*.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] Another legacy may be the sheep-counting system *yan tan tethera* in the north, in the traditionally Celtic areas of England such as Cumbria.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] Several words of Cornish origin are still in use in English as mining-related terms, including costean, gunnies, and vug.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] Those who argue against the theory of a more significant Brittonic influence than is widely accepted point out that many toponyms have no semantic continuation from the Brittonic language.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] A notable example is *Avon* which comes from the Celtic term for river *abona* or the Welsh term for river, *afon*, but was used by the English as a personal name.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] Likewise the River Ouse, Yorkshire, contains the Celtic word *usa* which merely means 'water' and the name of the river Trent simply comes from the Welsh word for a 'trespasser' (figuratively suggesting 'overflowing river').
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] Scholars supporting a Brittonic substrate in English argue that the use of periphrastic constructions (using auxiliary verbs such as *do* and *be* in the continuous/progressive) of the English verb, which is more widespread than in the other Germanic languages, is traceable to Brittonic influence.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] Others, however, find this unlikely since many of these forms are only attested in the later Middle English period; these scholars claim a native English development rather than Celtic influence.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] Roberts postulates Northern Germanic influence, despite such constructions not existing in Norse.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] Literary Welsh has the simple present *Caraf* = 'I love' and the present stative (al. continuous/progressive) *Yr wyf yn caru* = 'I am loving', where the Brittonic syntax is partly mirrored in English.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] (However, English *I am loving* comes from older *I am a-loving*, from still older *ich am on luvende* 'I am in the process of loving').
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] 'I am working' is *Ich bin am Arbeiten*, literally: 'I am on the working'.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] The same structure is also found in modern Dutch (*Ik ben aan het werk*), alongside other structures (e.g.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] These parallel developments suggest that the English progressive is not necessarily due to Celtic influence; moreover, the native English development of the structure can be traced over 1000 years and more of English literature.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] Some researchers (Filppula, et al., 2001) argue that other elements of English syntax reflect Brittonic influences.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] For instance, in English tag questions, the form of the tag depends on the verb form in the main statement (*aren't I?*, *isn't he?*, *won't we?*, etc.).
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] The German *nicht wahr?* and the French *n'est-ce pas?*, by contrast, are fixed forms which can be used with almost any main statement.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] It has been claimed that the English system has been borrowed from Brittonic, since Welsh tag questions vary in almost exactly the same way.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] Far more notable, but less well known, are Brittonic influences on Scottish Gaelic, though Scottish and Irish Gaelic, with their wider range of preposition-based periphrastic constructions, suggest that such constructions descend from their common Celtic heritage.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] Scottish Gaelic contains several P-Celtic loanwords, but, as there is a far greater overlap in terms of Celtic vocabulary than with English, it is not always possible to disentangle P- and Q-Celtic words.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] However, some common words such as *monadh* = Welsh *mynydd*, Cumbric *monidh* are particularly evident.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] The Brittonic influence on Scots Gaelic is often indicated by considering Irish language usage, which is not likely to have been influenced so much by Brittonic.
[src:beurla-reagaird/brittonic-languages] In particular, the word *srath* (anglicised as "strath") is a native Goidelic word, but its usage appears to have been modified by the Welsh cognate *ystrad* whose meaning is slightly different.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] Bungi has been categorized as a post-creole, with the distinctive features of the language gradually abandoned by successive generations of speakers in favour of standard Canadian English.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] In 1870, about 5,000 Métis were native speakers of Bungi, but by the late 1980s, only a handful of elderly speakers were known.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] Today, Bungi has very few if any speakers and is potentially extinct.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] Bungi was spoken in the Lower Red River Colony in the area from The Forks (where the Red River and Assiniboine River meet in what is now downtown Winnipeg) to the mouth of the Red River at Lake Winnipeg.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] This is the area where the English/Scottish retired Hudson's Bay Company servants generally settled.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] Over the years, Bungi has been spelled many different ways by many different people, and was often referred to simply as the Red River Dialect.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] Expanded scholarship has preferred "Bungi" as the preferred spelling over "Bungee" and other spellings.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] The name derives from either Ojibwe: *bangii*, or Cree: *pahkī*, both words meaning *a little bit*.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] In these colloquial uses the term may have mildly pejorative connotations, even when used by speakers to describe themselves.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] Bungi is unusual as a dialect in that for the Scottish immigrants and the First Nations who developed the dialect, English was often a second language.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] Others, such as Brian Orvis, a Bungi-speaker from Selkirk, Manitoba, argued that Bungi is a language unto its own.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] He asserted that Bungee-speakers do not like to be recorded speaking the language because the First Nations values are that one should not call attention to oneself.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] It is because of this, he argues, that it is difficult to document Bungi, and the speakers will often deny knowledge of the language.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] In addition to the being the name of a dialect, the word Bungi might have referred to a specific group of Métis of Scottish ancestry.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] The earliest records report that the name "Bungee" was used by the British, and especially Hudson's Bay Company employees to refer to the Saulteaux.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] Sometime around the turn of the 20th century, the word Bungi began to be used to refer to people of Scottish and First Nations ancestry.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] The most notable particularity of Bungi is its phonology (sound system and pronunciation).
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] Voice quality differences are also apparent.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] The lexicon is mostly English with borrowings from Gaelic, Cree, Ojibwa, and other languages.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] Margaret Stobie studied Bungi and visited several communities where Bungi was spoken.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] In her 1971 article, *The Dialect Called Bungi*, Stobie reported that Bungi was the English dialect spoken by the descendants of Gaelic-speaking Highlanders.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] Blain conducted one of the most thorough academic studies of Bungi in her thesis and other publications, *The Bungee Dialect of the Red River Settlement* (1989).
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] Blain's research found extremely negative attitudes to Bungi among the population which had spoken it in previous generations, a factor which likely contributed to its near extinction by the time of her research.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] The study records the dialect in its final phase, when considerable levelling towards standard Canadian English was present.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] Bungi was spoken with a distinctive rhythm with a Gaelic fall, including the way that syllables are stressed, repetition of both nouns and pronouns in a sentence (e.g.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] "My brother is coming, him."), changes in the pronunciation of phonemes (e.g. the phonemic distinction between [s] and [š] in not present in Western Cree dialects, and were reversed in Bungi from the standard English), etc.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] The third-person pronouns in Cree do not distinguish between masculine and feminine, which resulted in the interchangeable use of he and she in Bungi without regard for gender (e.g.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] Bungee borrowed words and structures from the parent languages (e.g. the standard Bungee greeting of "I'm well, you but?" came directly from Cree).
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] Bungi speakers also reported that Bungi uses Cree vowels and Scots consonants.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] Prior to 1938, people were already expressing concerns about the potential loss of Bungi.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] In letters to the *Winnipeg Evening Tribune*, Mr.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] Moncrief, writing under the pen name "Old Timer," and Osborne Scott expressed their concerns about the survival of the Red River dialect.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] Others wrote in letters to the editor of the same newspaper in 1938 that Bungi would be gone in a generation.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] Blain also notes that Bungi was in a constant state of change that was evolving towards the local standard English.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] Swan also reports the prejudice towards Bungi speakers in her thesis, *Ethnicity and the Canadianization of Red River Politics* (1991).
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] She suggests that Anglo-Métis Manitoba Premier John Norquay, who was born near St.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] Andrews in what was the Red River Colony and would have spoken Bungi, had dropped his accent by the time that he had entered politics.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] The social prejudice towards Bungi speakers and the very sensitive linguistic environment ultimately led to the extinction of this dialect.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] The main linguistic documentation of this dialect were conducted by Eleanor M.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] Osborne Scott also contributed to the understanding of Bungi (1937, 1951).
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] In an article titled *Red River Dialect* published in 1936 under the pseudonym Old Timer (a nom de plume commonly used by J.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] Moncrieef who was from the Shetland Islands), the author provided an excerpt from a letter that had some Bungi.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] — Osborne Scott, Winnipeg Evening Tribune.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] Another story was recounted in the same article.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] Scott also recounted a discussion that he had overheard.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] Scott also recounted a discussion that he had been a part of.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] Scott said that First Nations words were used in Bungi most often as "picturesque short words, generally exclamatory".
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] In addition, the names of birds, animals, and plants were commonly First Nations words, as these things were new to the immigrants.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] In a later, updated version of the article in 1951 that included parts of the original radio broadcast that were not in The Winnipeg Evening Tribune article, Osborne also told of a young Canon M.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] Sanderson learning to pronounce [s] and [š] under the tutelage of Rev.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] The letter was in response to an irate letter titled *Not Offensive to Red River Descendants* about Scott's article submitted by Mrs.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] Kipling felt that Scott had belittled and insulted the Bungi speakers of the Red River, when in fact Osborne and another contributor (likely Mr.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] Moncrieff under the pseudonym An Old Timer) were saddened by the vanishing of Bungi and that their children would not know the accents and dialect, and wanted to remember the humour as well.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] — Bung-gay (Islay Mary Sinclair), *Winnipeg Evening Tribune*.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] In another letters to the editor in support of Scott, called *Oldtimer Appreciates Osborne Scott's Article*, Mary I.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] She also included a few stories of nicknames, such as a family by the name of Johnstone who were christened with "Teapot" for their addiction to tea, which was more familiar and seen as a distinguishing mark for them.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] Another example of Bungi with a standard English translation is provided through Red River North Heritage as a part of their geocache work.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] This is Rachel Bunn telling the story of how her husband, Thomas Bunn, built a stone house known as Victoria Cottage (which is now a historic site).
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] A modern recording of this being spoken is also available on the Red River North Heritage website.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] The exact origin of this text is not provided.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] Me Thomas thur built ma a hoose so solid he built it.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] Samuel Taylor put a handle on it een sixta-too ye-naw-see.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] Every marnin back and fore he come across from the stone fort—he worked thur but.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] He built the English tsarts you know on the cross side.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] Loang-headed is my Thomas Bunn is loang-headed.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] Me hoose, mind dese wallis are stone and tree foot tick you know.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] Aye, so calm this ruvvers bein no, doon be fooled!
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] We fled maina males to the paines and had a sweet time.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] Mind, tanks to my Thomas Bunn, fein and coomfortable we are sertently and saiventa foot haigh from the ruvver—we'll not fluid ere.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] I'm sure it will stand forever, I think!
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] Samuel Taylor put the finishing touches on it in 1862.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] Every morning back and forth he came across the river from Lower Fort Garry, where he worked.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] He built St Clements Mapleton church across the river.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] My house, the walls are stone and three feet thick!
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] So calm this Red River is but don't be fooled!
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] Come spring the river is very ill-tempered!
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] South of us, when we were upriver in Kildonan, the river nearly took our house in the big flood in 1852.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] We fled many miles to the high ground at Bird's Hill and had a difficult time.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] Now thanks to Thomas we are certainly comfortable seventy feet above the river and will never flood again!
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] Mulligan wrote the story of Little Red Riding Hood as it would have been told in Bungi, titled *The Shtory of Little Red Ridin Hood*].
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] Frank Walters was a historian that was interested in preserving Bungi heritage.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bungi-dialect] He conducted a study of Bungi, and made a series of recordings known as the *Bungee Collection* (also known as the *Walters Collection*).
[src:beurla-reagaird/bunscoill-ghaelgagh] In 1999 a parents' society, *Sheshaght ny Paarantyn*, was formed with an interest in establishing a Manx-language school.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bunscoill-ghaelgagh] That year they approached the Isle of Man's Department of Education with their request.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bunscoill-ghaelgagh] At the time it had one class and shared premises at Ballacottier School in Douglas.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bunscoill-ghaelgagh] In January 2003 it moved to its own building in the old St John's School.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bunscoill-ghaelgagh] The school won the annual *Reih Bleeaney Vanannan* award in January 2006 for its efforts in preserving and promoting Manx language, culture and heritage.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bunscoill-ghaelgagh] It was presented by the then Speaker of the House of Keys, James "Tony" Brown, chairman of the Manx Heritage Foundation.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bunscoill-ghaelgagh] Numbers continued to increase, from nine in 2001 when the school moved to its current premises to 47 in 2006, then to 65 in 2009 and 69 in 2012.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bunscoill-ghaelgagh] The school is considered successful and is part of the Manx language revival.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bunscoill-ghaelgagh] After UNESCO listed the language as extinct in 2009, pupils wrote letters asking "If our language is extinct then what language are we writing in?", and the classification was later changed to "critically endangered".
[src:beurla-reagaird/bunscoill-ghaelgagh] Lewis Carroll's *Alice in Wonderland* (*Ealish ayns Çheer ny Yindyssyn*) is read in translation after 30 copies were presented to the *Bunscoill Ghaelgagh* by the Manx Gaelic Society when the book was officially launched.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bunscoill-ghaelgagh] The school itself refers to studies that have been made in Finland that demonstrate advantages from bilingual education.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bunscoill-ghaelgagh] Researcher Aini-Kristiina Jäppinen examined the achievement of 334 pupils in 12 schools on "content and language-integrated learning" programmes and compared them with 334 pupils studying only in Finnish.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bunscoill-ghaelgagh] She concluded that a foreign language adds to the learning process and seems to improve results.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bunscoill-ghaelgagh] As the school notes, this conclusion is not universal to other previous studies.
[src:beurla-reagaird/bunscoill-ghaelgagh] Studies at Luton University have shown that there can be a "trivial" delay in language development but the overall benefits in the long run outweigh this temporary disadvantage.
[src:beurla-reagaird/callaecian-language] Classical authors Pomponius Mela, Pliny the Elder, and Strabo wrote about the existence of Celtic and non-Celtic populations in Callaecia.
[src:beurla-reagaird/callaecian-language] Most linguists consider Callaecia to be part of a common dialect continuum with Lusitania.
[src:beurla-reagaird/callaecian-language] There is controversy over the classification of the Lusitanian language.
[src:beurla-reagaird/callaecian-language] Although most scholars regard it as a non-Celtic Indo-European language, some argue that it is a Celtic language with archaic features.
[src:beurla-reagaird/callaecian-language] Apart from the Lusitanian-like elements, Celtic linguistic records abound in Callaecia as they do in Lusitania.
[src:beurla-reagaird/callaecian-language] Below are listed some hypothetical Celtic etymologies for various linguistic records from ancient Callaecia.
[src:beurla-reagaird/callaecian-language] Under the P/Q Celtic hypothesis, Callaecian appears to be a Q-Celtic language, as evidenced by the following occurrences in local inscriptions: ARQVI, ARCVIVS, ARQVIENOBO, ARQVIENI[S], ARQVIVS, all probably from IE Paleo-Hispanic **arkʷios* 'archer, bowman', retaining proto-Celtic **kʷ*.
[src:beurla-reagaird/callaecian-language] It is also noteworthy the ethnonyms *Equaesi* ( < PIE **ek̂wos* 'horse'), a people from southern Callaecia, and the *Querquerni* ( < **perkʷ-* 'oak').
[src:beurla-reagaird/camunic-language] The **Camunic language** is an extinct language that was spoken in the 1st millennium BC in Val Camonica, a valley in the Central Alps.
[src:beurla-reagaird/camunic-language] The language is sparsely attested to an extent that makes any classification attempt uncertain—even the discussion of whether it should be considered a pre–Indo-European or an Indo-European language has remained indecisive.
[src:beurla-reagaird/camunic-language] Among several suggestions, it has been hypothesized that Camunic is related to the Raetic language from the Tyrsenian language family, or to the Celtic languages.
[src:beurla-reagaird/camunic-language] There are at least 170 known inscriptions, the majority of which are only a few words long.
[src:beurla-reagaird/camunic-language] The writing system used is a variant of the north-Etruscan alphabet, known as the *Camunian alphabet* or *alphabet of Sondrio*.
[src:beurla-reagaird/camunic-language] Longer inscriptions show that Camunic writing used boustrophedon.
[src:beurla-reagaird/camunic-language] Its name derives from the people of the Camunni, who lived during the Iron Age in Valcamonica and were the creators of many of the stone carvings in the area.
[src:beurla-reagaird/camunic-language] Abecedariums found in Nadro and Piancogno have been dated to between 500 BC and 50 AD.
[src:beurla-reagaird/camunic-language] The amount of material is insufficient to fully decipher the language.
[src:beurla-reagaird/camunic-language] Some scholars think it may be related to Raetic and to Etruscan, but it is considered premature to make such affiliation.
[src:beurla-reagaird/camunic-language] Other scholars suggest that Camunic could be a Celtic or another unknown Indo-European language.
